ngfacts'', n.d. Anderson talked in the interview of having, in late 1967, a day job cleaning Luton's Ritz Cinema. Retrieved 6 March 2013.</ref>\n* [[Rodney Bewes]], actor\n* [[Mo Chaudry]], entrepreneur\n* [[Diana Dors]], actress<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bedsarchives.bedford.gov.uk/CommunityArchives/Luton/LicensedinLuton/The-English-Rose-Public-House-Luton.aspx|title=The English Rose Public House Luton|last=|first=|date=|website=Bedford Borough Council|access-date=|quote=During the 1950s a regular visitor was actress Diana Dors, whose first husband Dennis Hamilton was the son of landlord Stanley Gittins. She is said to have served behind the bar in the pub on a number of occasions.}}</ref>\n* [[Ian Dury]], singer<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iandury.com/Biography/|title=Ian Dury - A brief biography|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|quote=Ian found part-time work as an Art teacher at Luton College of Further Technology}}</ref>\n* [[John Hegley]], poet\n* [[Hilda Hewlett]], UK's first female pilot\n* [[Alec Jeffreys|Sir Alec Jeffreys]], geneticist\n* [[Sarfraz Manzoor]], author and columnist, [[The Guardian]]\n* [[Eric Morecambe]], entertainer\n* [[Elizabeth Price (artist)|Elizabeth Price]], artist\n* [[Colin Salmon]], actor\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|England}}\n{{columns-list|\n<!--Relevant lists-->\n* [[List of places in Luton]]\n* [[List of schools in Luton]]\n* [[List of towns in England]]\n* [[List of unitary authorities of England]]\n* [[List of urban areas in the United Kingdom]]\n<!--Subarticles-->\n* [[History of Luton]]\n* [[Demography of Luton]]\n* [[Economy of Luton]]\n* [[Politics in Luton]]\n* [[Transport in Luton]]\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Dyer |first1=James |last2=Stygall |first2=Frank |last3=Dony |first3=John |year=1964 |title=The Story of Luton |location=Luton |publisher=White Crescent Press |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Collier's Poster|year=1921}}\n{{Commons and category|Luton}}\n{{wikivoyage|Luton}}\n* {{OpenDomesday|TL0821|luton|Luton}}\n* {{Britannica|352186}}\n* [https://www.luton.gov.uk Luton Borough Council]\n* {{YouTube|u=lutonboroughcouncil|Luton Borough Council}}\n* [https://www.bedfordshire.police.uk Bedfordshire Police]\n* [https://www.bedsfire.gov.uk Bedfordshire Fire and Rescue]\n* [https://www.ldh.nhs.uk Luton and Dunstable] - major local hospital\n* [https://www.lutontoday.co.uk Luton Today] - local news\n* [https://www.lutonculture.com Luton Culture] - charity which manages museums and various events\n* [https://www.lutontown.co.uk Luton Town F.C.] - local [[Association football|football]] team\n\n{{Adjacent communities|state=expanded\n |Centre = Luton\n |NW = [[Milton Keynes]]\n |N  = [[Bedford]]\n |NE = [[Hitchin]]\n |W  = [[Dunstable]]\n |E  = [[Stevenage]]\n |SW = [[Berkhamsted]]\n |S  = [[Hemel Hempstead]]\n |SE = [[Harpenden]]\n}}\n{{Luton|state=expanded}}\n{{Bedfordshire}}\n{{Unitary authorities of England}}\n{{East of England}}\n{{River Lee England}}\n{{London commuter belt}}\n{{Coord|51|53|N|0|25|W|region:GB_type:city|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Luton| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Hat making]]\n[[Category:Local government districts of Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Unitary authority districts of England]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 6th century]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Bedfordshire]]\n", "name_user": "82.17.236.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLeisure and entertainment)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luton"}
{"title_page": "South Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref>), and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=\"ref1\"/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=\"ref8\">{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=Powlesland/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=Powlesland/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=PowleslandBolton>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=Powlesland/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=\"ref2\"/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=\"ref8\"/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=\"ref16\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref>), and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=\"ref1\"/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=\"ref8\">{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=\"ref12\">{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=\"ref14\">{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=Powlesland>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=\"ref2\"/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=\"ref8\"/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=\"ref16\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBreeding:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Grand Prior's Award", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Grand Prior Award Badge.jpg|150px|thumb|right|The Grand Prior Award]]\nThe '''Grand Prior's Award''',<ref name=\"NZ\">{{Cite web|url=https://youth.stjohn.org.nz/public/what-we-do/cadet-programme/|title=Hey Everyone! I've just been awarded my Grand Prior Award.|website=St John Youth}}</ref> also called the '''Grand Prior Award''',<ref name=\"GPA\" /> named for [[Grand Prior]] of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]], is the highest award that a cadet in the [[St. John Ambulance]] Youth Programme can achieve. The Grand Prior's Award recognises a self-motivated and capable young person's ongoing commitment, compassion, and support. It is recognised and awarded internationally by various branches of the program. The Grand Prior's Award is recognised in many countries, including [[St John Ambulance Cadets in the UK|England and the Islands]], [[St John Ambulance in Wales|Wales]], [[St. John Ambulance Canada|Canada]], [[St. John Ambulance of Malaysia|Malaysia]], [[St John Youth New Zealand|New Zealand]], and [[St John Ambulance Australia Cadets|Australia]].\n\n== England and the Islands ==\nCadets begin to work on the Grand Prior's Award scheme after receiving the Membership award.<ref name=\"GPA\" /> The award scheme was named for the Grand Prior's of the Order of St John, the [[Duke of Gloucester]]. The award scheme involves cadets completing 24 subjects at different levels. Eight subjects must be completed for the bronze level, eight more for silver, and a further four for gold. After completing another four subjects, the cadet will be awarded with the Grand Prior's Award.<ref name=\"GPA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sja.org.uk/sja/young-people/cadets/grand-prior-award.aspx|title=Grand Prior Award|website=Sja.org.uk}}</ref> Cadets can continue to work on this award until they are 21 years old.\n\n== Malaysia ==\n[[File:Grand Prior Award.jpg|thumb|Recipients of the Grand Prior's Award in Malaysia]]\nIn its early years, the scheme had a different subject group (cycling, camping, tracking, etc.) than is used today. These groups were removed and merged to make the scheme that is currently used today. The 26 badges are split into five different groups according to the nature of the activities. These groups are: care, emergency care, leisure, communication, and life and social skills.\n\nCadets who successfully complete the Grand Prior's Award receive the award from the Order Secretariat in London, England. Cadets who obtain the Grand Prior's Award are known as Grand Prior Cadets and can wear the badge as adult members throughout their service in St John Ambulance.<ref name=\"Malaysia\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sjam.org.my/our-actvivities/st-john-cadets-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110235329/http://www.sjam.org.my/our-actvivities/st-john-cadets-1 |archive-date=10 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Badge requirements===\n* 12 proficiency badges in total (include \"Knowledge of the Order\" badge)\n* Took '''AT LEAST 1 badge''' and '''NOT MORE THAN 3 badges''' from each category\n* The individual must be less than 21 years old on the date of assessment for their last badge\n* To apply GRAND PRIOR AWARD before 16 years old must had 4 badge.\n\n===Badges===\n* Knowledge of the Order (compulsory)\n\n==== Care ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Animal Care\n* Care in the Community\n* Caring for the Sick\n* Caring for Children\n* Anti Drug Abuse\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Emergency Care ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Accident Prevention\n* Fire Fighting and Prevention\n* Casualty Simulation\n* Personal Survival and Life Saving\n* Civil Defence\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Leisure ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Outdoor Pursuits\n* Fitness\n* Craft\n* Map Reading and Navigation\n* Musician\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Communication ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Communication to the Impaired\n* Administration Skills\n* Computer Skills\n* Signalling\n* International Friendship\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Life and Social Skills ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Citizenship\n* Home Skills\n* Cookery and Nutrition\n* Do-It-Yourself\n* Cadet Training Course\n{{div col end}}\n\n== New Zealand ==\nIn New Zealand, the proficiency badges are split into three levels: green (8\u201310 years), blue (11\u201312 years), and gold (13\u201318 years). Different level badges have different coloured frames and have learning criteria suited to the age range, with gold level being the most difficult. Only the gold level badges count towards the Grand Prior's Award. A cadet must achieve the six compulsory badges and six badges of their choice to be awarded the Grand Prior's Award.<ref name=\"NZ\" /> There are 29 badges to choose from.<ref name=\"NZ\" />\n\n===Badge requirements===\n* Complete six gold level compulsory subjects and six other gold level badges\n* The cadet must be less than 21 years old on the date of assessment for their last badge\n* The first gold level badge must be completed prior to the cadet's 18th birthday\n* The cadet must have completed at least 100 hours of community service\n\n===Gold level badges===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Accident Prevention\n* Animal Care\n* Camping\n* Caregivers (compulsory)\n* Casualty Simulation\n* Child Care\n* Civil Defence\n* Communication (compulsory)\n* Community Awareness (compulsory)\n* Drill (compulsory)\n* Environment\n* Faith\n* Fire Safety\n* First Aid (compulsory)\n* Fitness\n* Hauora (Health)\n* Hobbies\n* Home Technology\n* Global Citizenship\n* Information Communication Technology\n* Leadership\n* Maoritanga\n* Road Safety\n* St John (compulsory)\n* The Arts\n* Ventureship\n* Water Safety\n* Kiwiana\n* Media Studies\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Australia ==\nThe [[St John Ambulance Australia Cadets#Grand Prior.27s badge|Grand Prior's Badge]] is the highest award that a cadet can receive and is awarded to cadets who have earned 12 proficiency badges, including the Knowledge of the Order Badge and the Family Care Badge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadets.stjohn.org.au/index.php/challenge-cadets|title=Challenge|author=<!--Super User-->|website=Stjohn.org.au}}</ref> The first Grand Prior's badges in the world were awarded in 1933 to three cadets; two were from the United Kingdom, and the other, Marion Higgins from Marrickville Cadet Nursing Division, was from Australia. The award is worn on the left sleeve for as long as the cadet remains a member of the Operations Branch and is one of the only cadet badges that can be worn as an adult.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{St John Ambulance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand Prior's Award}}\n[[Category:Humanitarian and service awards]]\n[[Category:St. John Ambulance]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n[[File:Grand Prior Award Badge.jpg|150px|thumb|right|The Grand Prior Award]]\nThe '''Grand Prior's Award''',<ref name=\"NZ\">{{Cite web|url=https://youth.stjohn.org.nz/public/what-we-do/cadet-programme/|title=Hey Everyone! I've just been awarded my Grand Prior Award.|website=St John Youth}}</ref> also called the '''Grand Prior Award''',<ref name=\"GPA\" /> named for [[Grand Prior]] of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John]], is the highest award that a cadet in the [[St. John Ambulance]] Youth Programme can achieve. The Grand Prior's Award recognizes a self-motivated and capable young person's ongoing commitment, compassion, and support. It is recognized and awarded internationally by various branches of the program. The Grand Prior's Award is recognized in many countries, including [[St John Ambulance Cadets in the UK|England and the Islands]], [[St John Ambulance in Wales|Wales]], [[St. John Ambulance Canada|Canada]], [[St. John Ambulance of Malaysia|Malaysia]], [[St John Youth New Zealand|New Zealand]], and [[St John Ambulance Australia Cadets|Australia]].\n\n== England and the Islands ==\nCadets begin to work on the Grand Prior's Award scheme after receiving the Membership award.<ref name=\"GPA\" /> The award scheme was named for the Grand Prior's of the Order of St John, the [[Duke of Gloucester]]. The award scheme involves cadets completing 24 subjects at different levels. Eight subjects must be completed for the bronze level, eight more for silver, and a further four for gold. After completing another four subjects, the cadet will be awarded with the Grand Prior's Award.<ref name=\"GPA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sja.org.uk/sja/young-people/cadets/grand-prior-award.aspx|title=Grand Prior Award|website=Sja.org.uk}}</ref> Cadets can continue to work on this award until they are 21 years old.\n\n== Malaysia ==\n[[File:Grand Prior Award.jpg|thumb|Recipients of the Grand Prior's Award in Malaysia]]\nIn its early years, the scheme had a different subject group (cycling, camping, tracking, etc.) than is used today. These groups were removed and merged to make the scheme that is currently used today. The 26 badges are split into five different groups according to the nature of the activities. These groups are: care, emergency care, leisure, communication, and life and social skills.\n\nCadets who successfully complete the Grand Prior's Award receive the award from the Order Secretariat in London, England. Cadets who obtain the Grand Prior's Award are known as Grand Prior Cadets and can wear the badge as adult members throughout their service in St John Ambulance.<ref name=\"Malaysia\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sjam.org.my/our-actvivities/st-john-cadets-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-11-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110235329/http://www.sjam.org.my/our-actvivities/st-john-cadets-1 |archive-date=2013-11-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Badge requirements===\n* 12 proficiency badges in total (include \"Knowledge of the Order\" badge)\n* Took '''AT LEAST 1 badge''' and '''NOT MORE THAN 3 badges''' from each category\n* The individual must be less than 21 years old on the date of assessment for their last badge\n* To apply GRAND PRIOR AWARD before 16 years old must had 4 badge.\n\n===Badges===\n* Knowledge of the Order (compulsory)\n\n==== Care ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Animal Care\n* Care in the Community\n* Caring for the Sick\n* Caring for Children\n* Anti Drug Abuse\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Emergency Care ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Accident Prevention\n* Fire Fighting and Prevention\n* Casualty Simulation\n* Personal Survival and Life Saving\n* Civil Defence\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Leisure ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Outdoor Pursuits\n* Fitness\n* Craft\n* Map Reading and Navigation\n* Musician\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Communication ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Communication to the Impaired\n* Administration Skills\n* Computer Skills\n* Signalling\n* International Friendship\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Life and Social Skills ====\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Citizenship\n* Home Skills\n* Cookery and Nutrition\n* Do-It-Yourself\n* Cadet Training Course\n{{div col end}}\n\n== New Zealand ==\nIn New Zealand, the proficiency badges are split into three levels: green (8\u201310 years), blue (11\u201312 years), and gold (13\u201318 years). Different level badges have different coloured frames and have learning criteria suited to the age range, with gold level being the most difficult. Only the gold level badges count towards the Grand Prior's Award. A cadet must achieve the six compulsory badges and six badges of their choice to be awarded the Grand Prior's Award.<ref name=\"NZ\" /> There are 29 badges to choose from.<ref name=\"NZ\" />\n\n===Badge requirements===\n* Complete six gold level compulsory subjects and six other gold level badges\n* The cadet must be less than 21 years old on the date of assessment for their last badge\n* The first gold level badge must be completed prior to the cadet's 18th birthday\n* The cadet must have completed at least 100 hours of community service\n\n===Gold level badges===\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Accident Prevention\n* Animal Care\n* Camping\n* Caregivers (compulsory)\n* Casualty Simulation\n* Child Care\n* Civil Defence\n* Communication (compulsory)\n* Community Awareness (compulsory)\n* Drill (compulsory)\n* Environment\n* Faith\n* Fire Safety\n* First Aid (compulsory)\n* Fitness\n* Hauora (Health)\n* Hobbies\n* Home Technology\n* Global Citizenship\n* Information Communication Technology\n* Leadership\n* Maoritanga\n* Road Safety\n* St John (compulsory)\n* The Arts\n* Ventureship\n* Water Safety\n* Kiwiana\n* Media Studies\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Australia ==\nThe [[St John Ambulance Australia Cadets#Grand Prior.27s badge|Grand Prior's Badge]] is the highest award that a cadet can receive and is awarded to cadets who have earned 12 proficiency badges, including the Knowledge of the Order Badge and the Family Care Badge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadets.stjohn.org.au/index.php/challenge-cadets|title=Challenge|author=<!--Super User-->|website=Stjohn.org.au}}</ref> The first Grand Prior's badges in the world were awarded in 1933 to three cadets; two were from the [[United Kingdom]], and the other, Marion Higgins from Marrickville Cadet Nursing Division, was from Australia. The award is worn on the left sleeve for as long as the cadet remains a member of the Operations Branch and is one of the only cadet badges that can be worn as an adult.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{St John Ambulance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand Prior's Award}}\n[[Category:Humanitarian and service awards]]\n[[Category:St. John Ambulance]]\n", "name_user": "Ohconfucius", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perMOS:NUM,MOS:CAPS,MOS:LINK, EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Prior%27s_Award"}
{"title_page": "Al Faiz family", "text_new": "The family of '''Al Faiz''' ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0641\u0627\u0626\u0632\u200e|\u02be\u0100l F\u0101\u02beiz}}), also transliterated in a number of other ways, including '''Al''' '''Fa'iz''', '''Al Fa'ez''', '''Al''' '''Faez''', or '''Al Fayez''', is the oldest [[Alids|Alid]] family of [[Karbala]], which they have occupied, on some occasions ruled, and held custodianship of its holy sites, since 861.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book|last=Sadr|first=Sayyid Hassan|url=http://ar.lib.eshia.ir/27315/1/479|title=Nuzhat Ahl al-Haramayn Fi 'Imarat al-Mashhadayn|publisher=|year=1965|isbn=|location=Lucknow, India|pages=21|language=Arabic|trans-title=A Stroll Into the Sights of the Shrines}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=12|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Holy shrines of Karbala : architectural study with a historical background of the area between and around the two holy shrines of Karbala-Iraq|url=https://repository.uwtsd.ac.uk/1030/|publisher=University of Wales Trinity Saint David|date=1997-06-30|degree=doctoral|language=en|first=R. M.|last=Ali Al-Ansari}} p. 48.</ref>{{Infobox noble house|surname=House of Faiz|native_name=\u0622\u0644 \u0641\u0627\u0626\u0632|native_name_lang=Arabic|other_name=Faizids|alt=|caption=|image_size=|type=|parent house=A branch of [[Ibrahim al-Mujab]], of [[Al-Musawi|Musawi]], of [[Banu Hashim]], of [[Quraysh]]|founded={{Start date and years ago|861}} in [[Karbala]]|founder=[[Ibrahim al-Mujab]] <br/> [[Al Faiz family#Notable Figures|Mohammed Abu al-Faiz]]|current head={{plainlist|\n*{{smaller|Tuma:}} Muhi Mustafa Tuma\n*{{smaller|Nasrallah:}} Muhammad-Hussain Muhammad-Ali Nasrallah\n*{{smaller|Dhiya al-Din:}} Ahmed Abbod Dhiya al-Din}}|dissolution=|estates=Mahalat Al Faiz, FIdan al-Sada, Maal Yunis, Umm Ramila, Bustan Dhway, Maal Ju'an|notes=|styles=|cadet branches=|titles=* Naqib al-Ashraf\n* Saden al-Rawdhat\n* Ra'is al-Ha'ir\n* Hakim Karbala}}They are the descendants of [[Ibrahim al-Mujab]], the 9th-century grandson of the seventh Shi'ite Imam, [[Musa al-Kadhim]]. Their eponymous ancestor is considered to be [[Al Faiz family#Notable Figures|Muhammad Abu al-Faiz]], the 12th great grandson of al-Mujab. In Karbala, the family holds a high prestige where they maintained authority of the ''[[Naqib al-ashraf|niqaba]]'' (supervision) of Karbala's [[Sayyid|sayyids]] and the ''sidana'' (custodianship) of Karbala's holy sites numerous times over different periods.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Fadala|first=Dr. Saleh|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aathmwEACAAJ|title=al-Jawhar al-Afeef Fi Ma'rifat al-Nasab al-Nabawi al-Sharif|publisher=Dar al-Kotob al-Ilmiyah|year=2013|isbn=9782745178664|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=501\u2013502|trans-title=The Noble Prophetic Lineage}}</ref>\n\nThe family is currently known by the families of '''Al Tuma''', '''Al Nasrallah''', '''Al Dhiya al-Din''', '''Al Tajir, Al Ouj''', and '''Al Sayyid Amin'''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/books/tarikh/houses/01.html|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=8|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Alid settlement in Karbala ===\nAfter [[al-Mutawakkil]] was killed in 861, the Alids found peace under his son, [[al-Muntasir]], who helped keep them safe and protect them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Melchert|first=Christopher|date=1996|title=Religious Policies of the Caliphs from al-Mutawakkil to al-Muqtadir, A H 232-295/A D 847-908|journal=Islamic Law and Society|volume=3|issue=3|pages=330\u2013331|issn=0928-9380|jstor=3399413|doi=10.1163/1568519962599069}}</ref> The first known Alid to settle in Karbala was [[Ibrahim al-Mujab]] bin Muhammad al-Abid bin Musa al-Kadhim, also known as Taj al-Din Ibrahim al-Mujab''.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Madani|first=Dhamin bin Shadqam|url=http://www.masaha.org/book/view/1989-%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B2%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%88-%D8%B2%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%86%D8%B3%D8%A8-%D8%A3%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%A6%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B7%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1|title=Tuhfat al-Azhar Wa Zulal al-Anhar Fi Nasab al-A'imah al-Athar|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=280|language=Arabic|trans-title=Vase of Flowers and Heavenly Rivers of The Lineages of The Imams}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Husayni 'Naqeeb Halab'|first=Taj al-Din|url=https://archive.org/details/olomnasb_ymail_20161020_1655/mode/2up|title=Ghayat al-Ikhtisar Fi al-Buyutat al-Alawiya al-Mahfoodha Min al-Ghubar|publisher=|year=1893|isbn=|location=Egypt|pages=56|language=Arabic|trans-title=Extremely Brief Alid Households Protected From Dust}}</ref>\n\n=== Sidana and Niqaba ===\nAfter the Alid's settled, al-Mujab took responsibilities for the two holy shrines, and through this became known as ''saden'' (custodian of) ''al-rawdhat'' (the shrines), i.e. the head role tending to the holy shrines of Husayn and Abbas, which is known as the ''sidana''.\n\nThe sidana was passed down from al-Mujab to his eldest son, Muhammad, nicknamed ''al-Ha'iri'', as they lived in the Ha'ir (another name for Karbala), in 913.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=56|language=ar}}</ref> This then kept being passed on down as follows:\n\n* Ahmed Abu al-Tayyib (962\u2013995)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=57|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Custodianship of the Husayn Shrine}}</ref>\n* Ali al-Majthoor (995\u20131029)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=58|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Custodianship of the Husayn Shrine}}</ref>\n* Ahmed al-Ha'iri (1029\u20131068)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=59|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Custodianship of the Husayn Shrine}}</ref>\n* Ibrahim al-Ha'iri (1068\u20131097)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=61|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Custodianship of the Husayn Shrine}}</ref>\n* After Ibrahim, a [[sayyid]] from the descendants of [[Ali ibn Husayn Zayn al-Abidin|Ali Zayn al-Abidin]] took the sidana, and later many different figures, until it returned to the descendants of al-Mujab with Muhammad Abu al-Faiz in 1259.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr. Shaykh Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Husayniya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=London, UK|pages=71|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Custodianship of the Husayn Shrine}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 10th-century, the ''naqib'' (supervisor of) ''al-ashraf'' (the descendants of Muhammad) i.e. the head or supervisor of the descendants of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]], which is known as the ''niqaba'', was established, in Karbala, during the [[Buyid dynasty|Buyid]] era. Muhammad al-Husayni, a descendant of Zayn al-Abidin, took the niqaba and became the first naqib of the Ha'ir.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul-Sahib|url=|title=Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2018|isbn=|volume=2|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=206|language=Arabic|trans-title=HIstory of Karbala}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-'Umari|first=Ali|url=https://archive.org/details/olomnasb_ymail_20160830_1552/mode/2up|title=al-Majdi Fi Ansab al-Talibiyeen|last2=al-Mahdawi al-Damaghi|first2=Ahmed|publisher=Sitareh|year=2001|isbn=964-6121-59-4|location=Qom, Iran|pages=400|trans-title=The Pride In The Lineage of the Talibids}}</ref> After al-Husayni, Sharaf al-Din Ahmed, a descendant of al-Mujab took over as naqib in c. 985.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bin Karkosh|first=Shaykh Yusif|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qZAtAQAAIAAJ|title=Tarikh al-Hilla|publisher=al-Maktaba al-Haydariya|year=1965|isbn=|volume=2|location=|pages=25\u201326|language=Arabic|trans-title=History of Hilla}}</ref> His son, Ibrahim al-Ha'iri then took over in 1001, and then when he passed away in 1049, it went to other sayyids, until it returned to Muhammad Abu al-Faiz in 1259.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul-Sahib|url=|title=Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2018|isbn=|volume=2|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=292|language=Arabic|trans-title=HIstory of Karbala}}</ref>\n\nIt is also worthy to mention, that the niqaba and sidana in Karbala at some points in time, were merged, so whoever held the niqaba, would also be saden of the two holy shrines.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Khiru|first=Ramziya|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1ooHuAEACAAJ|title=Idarat al-Iraq Fi Sadr al-Islam|publisher=Dar al-Huriya lil-Tiba'a|year=1978|isbn=|location=Baghdad, Iraq|pages=355|language=Arabic|trans-title=Management of Iraq in the Heart of Islam}}</ref>\n\n=== Tribal feud ===\nBy 1317, the [[Ilkhanate|Ilkhanate state]] was disintegrating. This left the Euphrates region without a stable government. Karbala then split into two factions, Al Faiz and Al Zheek. The Faiz tribe were descendants of Muhammad al-Abid bin Musa al-Kadhim, and the Zheek tribe were descendants of Ibrahim al-Asghar bin Musa al-Kadhim. The city witnessed a feud that lasted for nearly half a century. The famous Moroccan traveller, [[Ibn Battuta]], witnessed the unrest when he visited Karbala in 1326.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tanji 'Ibn Battuta'|first=Mohammed|url=https://download-library-pdf-ebooks.com/18013-free-book|title=Tu\u1e25fet \u00fcl-Nuth\u0101r F\u012b Ghar\u0101'ib il-Em\u1e63\u0101r Wa 'Ajai'b al-Asf\u0101r|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-'Ulum|year=1987|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=231|language=Arabic|trans-title=A Masterpiece to Those Who Contemplate the Wonders of Cities and the Marvels of Travelling}}</ref>\n\nAl Faiz is older in residence in Karbala, since Ibrahim al-Mujab moved to Karbala in 861 during the rule of al-Muntasir. Many branches of descendants were formed from al-Mujab, but it was Muhammad Abu al-Faiz that later stood out and became their patriarch in Karbala. One must also understand that, the feud began during the late life of Abu al-Faiz, meaning his tribe couldn't have consisted of just his descendants, but rather, he had united all of his cousins under his name.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Mohammed Hussain|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/690|title=Baghiyat al-Nubala' Fi Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Matba'at al-Irshad|year=|isbn=|location=Baghdad, Iraq|pages=130|language=Arabic|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\nAs for the Zheek tribe, they are named after their patriarch Yahya ''Zheek'', great-great-great-grandson of Abdullah al-Ha'iri, the naqib of the Talibids that moved to Karbala in the early 11th-century. All of the al-Asghar descendants had united under their cousin, Zheek's name. Al Zheek today are known by the families of Al Thabit, Al Daraj (later Al Naqib) and Al Wahab. The Al Eshaiker and Al Jolokhan families were cousins of Al Zheek, and also took under their name.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Simawi|first=Sheikh Mohammed|url=https://alkafeel.net/library/prob/upload/325be5d26c5de971f5c9cc649adbc294.pdf|title=Majali al-Lutf bi-Ardh al-Taff|publisher=Al-Abbas Holy Shrine Library|year=2011|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=445|trans-title=Spheres Of Love In The Lands Of Taff}}</ref>\n\nAl Faiz believed that the ''niqaba'' of Karbala belonged to them because they were the older residing family, whilst Al Zheek believed it belonged to them because they previously held the niqaba of the Talibids of Iraq.\n\nDue to the continuous chaos as a result of the feud, as well as the destabilisation of the central government, a tribe, by the name of, Al Muhanna, claimed they wanted to end the unrest, and used this excuse to invade Karbala in 1355.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Mohammed Hassan|title=Madinat al-Husayn|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=2|location=|pages=139|language=Arabic|trans-title=City of Hussain}}</ref> They took full control of the city and the holy sites''.'' Shihab al-Din Al Muhanna declared himself the naqib of the Ha'ir.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Husayni 'Ibn 'Anba|first=Jamal al-Din|title='Umdat al-Talib Fi Ansab Abi Talib|publisher=al-Matba'a al-Haydariya|year=1961|isbn=|location=Najaf, Iraq|pages=337|language=Arabic|trans-title=}}</ref> When Al Faiz and Al Zheek realised what had happened, they decided to put aside their disputes, unite, and revolt against the invading al-Muhanna tribe. With their rebellion, they managed to oust the naqib, and exile him and his tribe, out of the city.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Simawi|first=Sheikh Mohammed|url=https://alkafeel.net/library/prob/upload/325be5d26c5de971f5c9cc649adbc294.pdf|title=Majali al-Lutf bi-Ardh al-Taff|publisher=Al-Abbas Holy Shrine Library|year=2011|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=447|trans-title=Spheres Of Love In The Lands Of Taff}}</ref> The two tribes then formed an alliance, and decided they will split the roles between them, where Muhammad Sharaf al-Din, grandson of Abu al-Faiz, became governor of Karbala and saden al-rawdhat, whilst Abu al-Qasim Muhammad, son of Yahya Zheek, became naqib. The two tribes also married from each other to further forge the two factions.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul-Sahib|url=|title=Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2018|isbn=|volume=2|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=320|language=Arabic|trans-title=HIstory of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Dress ===\n[[File:Aza al-Sada al-Khadam.jpg|thumb|Faizid Sayyids wearing the ''kashida'' and ''jubba'', Karbala 2017|alt=|left|242x242px]]In the 9th century, the Alids of Karbala dressed in traditional Arabic garments ([[turban]], [[thawb]] and [[Bisht (clothing)|bisht]]) that came in various colours, although green was the more common colour.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cab\u0101\u1e6dab\u0101\u02bc\u012b|first=Mu\u1e25ammad \u1e24usayn|url=https://alfeker.net/library.php?id=4080|title=Sunan al-Nabi|publisher=Mu\u02beassasat al-Nashr al-Isl\u0101m\u012b li-Jam\u0101\u02bfat al-Mudarris\u012bn|year=2006|isbn=|location=Qom, Iran|pages=173-82|trans-title=Ways of the Prophet}}</ref> Later in 1372, [[Al-Ashraf Sha'ban|Sultan Shaban]] introduced a kind of nobility with the privilege of wearing green turbans for the Alids; and to distinguish them from the Abbasid's black symbol.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Zanjani|first=Ibrahim|url=https://alfeker.net/library.php?id=4336|title=Kashkool Zanjani|publisher=Mu'asasat al-A'lami|year=1979|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=|language=Arabic & Persian|trans-title=Diary of Zanjani}}</ref>\n\nWith the rise of the popularity of the [[fez]] in the 19th century, in [[Ottoman Iraq]], Nasir Nasrallah imported fez's from [[Vienna]], and green [[shawl]] wool from [[England]], and created what is now known as a ''kashida'' (a fez with a green scarf wrapped around it). The kashida along with a ''jubba'' (long coat with sleeves and buttons, similar to a [[cassock]]), became the dress code of the Faizids, which was then adopted and turned into the official attire of the sadens and servants of the Husayn and Abbas shrines', and it quickly spread to the rest of the shrine cities of Iraq.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zmeyzim|first=Said|title=Karbala Fi al-'Uhood al-Madhiya|publisher=Dar al-Balagha|year=2015|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=|trans-title=Karbala in the Previous Eras}}</ref>\n\nThe kashida's differ slightly between Karbala and other cities. In Karbala, the wrapped green scarf is much longer and takes up half the of the fez, and it is wrapped in a way that overlaps, allowing the front side to be distinctive. However in [[Najaf]], the wrap is shorter, but there is still an overlap<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mail.burathanews.com/arabic/news/132967|title=al-Baydha Tu'akid Indhimam Udhu al-Qa'ima al-Iraqiya Ridhwan al-Killidar Ilayha|last=|first=|date=2011-08-10|website=Buratha News Outlet|language=ar-iq|trans-title=Picture of Ridhwan al-Killidar (Najaf)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>, whilst in [[Samarra]], it is much shorter, and there is no overlap in the wrap, forming a consistent line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.h-iftaa.com/2018/09/%d8%b3%d9%85%d8%a7%d8%ad%d8%a9-%d9%85%d9%81%d8%aa%d9%8a-%d8%ac%d9%85%d9%87%d9%88%d8%b1%d9%8a%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b9%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%82-%d9%8a%d9%84%d8%aa%d9%82%d9%8a-%d9%83%d9%80%d9%8a%d9%80%d8%af/|title=Samahat Mufti Jumhuriyat al-Iraq Yaltaqi Kilidar Samara|last=|first=|date=|website=Dar al-Ifta' al-Iraqi|language=ar|trans-title=Picture of Othman al-Killidar (Samarra)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n== Notable Figures ==\n\n=== Muhammad Abu al-Faiz ===\nHe is: <blockquote>'''Mo\u1e25ammed Abu al-Fa\u02beiz''' [[Patronymic|bin]] '''Abu al-\u1e24assan \u02bfAli''' bin '''A\u1e25med Jalal al-Din''' bin '''Abu Ja\u02bffar''' '''Mo\u1e25ammed''' bin '''Abu Ja\u02bffar Mo\u1e25ammed'''  bin '''Abu Ja\u02bffar Najm al-Din al-Aswad''' bin '''Abu Ja\u02bffar Mo\u1e25ammed''' bin '''\u02bfAli al-Ghareeq''' bin '''Mo\u1e25ammed al-Khair''' bin '''Abu al-\u1e24assan \u02bfAli al-Majthoor''' bin '''Abu al-\u1e6cayyib A\u1e25med''' bin '''Mo\u1e25ammed al-\u1e24a\u02beiri''' bin '''Ibrahim al-Muj\u0101b''' bin '''Mo\u1e25ammed al-\u02bfA\u0101bid''' bin '''Musa al-K\u0101thim'''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul-Sahib|url=|title=Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2018|isbn=|volume=2|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=289|language=Arabic|trans-title=HIstory of Karbala}}</ref></blockquote>He is the progenitor of the Tuma, Nasrallah, Dhiya al-Din, Tajir, Ouj and Sayyid Amin families. He is reported to have been a valiant and noble man, followed by the majority of the city. He was the one that united all of the branches from the descendants of al-Mujab, that resided in Karbala, under his name.<ref name=\":1\" /> Abu al-Faiz owned vast lands across Karbala and Shfatha.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Husayni 'Naqeeb Halab'|first=Taj al-Din|url=|title=Ghayat al-Ikhtisar Fi al-Buyutat al-Alawiya al-Mahfoodha Min al-Ghubar|publisher=|year=1893|isbn=|location=Egypt|pages=55|language=Arabic|trans-title=Extremely Brief Alid Households Protected From Dust}}</ref> In 1259, under the rule of [[Hulagu Khan|Hulegu]], he was made naqib and ruler of Karbala.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Mohammed Hassan|url=|title=Madinat al-Husayn|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=4|location=|pages=30\u201331|language=Arabic|trans-title=City of Hussain}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Mohammed Hassan|url=|title=Madinat al-Husayn|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=4|location=|pages=30|language=Arabic|trans-title=City of Hussain}}</ref> He died in the first third of the 14th-century, before the Al Muhanna tribe invasion.\n\n=== Ahmed Shams al-Din al-Faizi ===\n[[File:AhmedAbuHashim.jpg|thumb|Ahmed Shams al-Din's mausoleum in Shfatha|262x262px]]He was the son of Abu al-Faiz and one of the nobles of Karbala. In c. 1311, the Ilkhanate minister, [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani|Rashid al-Din]], called for Ahmed in Hilla, and ordered him to kill the naqib which they had instated over the Ilkhanate kingdom, Taj al-Din al-Lawi al-Aftasi,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Meri|first=Josef W.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=c1ZsBgAAQBAJ|title=Medieval Islamic Civilization: An Encyclopedia|date=2005-10-31|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-45596-5|location=|pages=667|language=en}}</ref> and his two sons, Hussain and Ali. In return, he promised that he will make him naqib. Upon hearing this, Ahmed strongly refused, and fled that night to Karbala, and remained in hiding until Rashid al-Din's motive was exposed, in 1318.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hirz al-Din|first=Mohammed Hussain|url=https://www.aljawadain.org/book-library-details.php?id=475&cat=239|title=Maraqid al-Ma'arif|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=1|location=|pages=86\u201387|language=Arabic|trans-title=Shrines of Notable Figures}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Minister of Ras al-Ayn (Shfatha) in 1334 by [[Abu Sa'id Bahadur Khan|Bahadur Khan]]. He died in 1349, and has a shrine and mosque in north west Shfatha.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Holy shrines of Karbala : architectural study with a historical background of the area between and around the two holy shrines of Karbala-Iraq|url=https://repository.uwtsd.ac.uk/1030/|publisher=University of Wales Trinity Saint David|date=1997-06-30|degree=doctoral|language=en|first=R. M.|last=Ali Al-Ansari}} p. 159.</ref>\n\n=== Muhammad Sharaf al-Din al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Ahmed Shams al-Din. After the exile of the al-Muhanna tribe in the last third of the 14th-century, Muhammad was made ruler of Karbala. In 1393, when [[Timur|Timur Lang's]] forces, under the command of his son [[Miran Shah]], defeated [[Ahmad Jalayir|Ahmed Jalayir]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mertsahinoglu.com/research/14th-century-annihilation-of-iraq/|title=14th century annihilation of Iraq - Mert Sahinoglu|website=mertsahinoglu.com|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> they entered Karbala, to which they were met with its noblemen, headed by Muhammad who was ruling the city. Just before the Timurid invasion, the saden, Shaykh Ali al-Khazin, had passed away, Miran saw that the most appropriate person to hold the sidana was Muhammad, so he appointed him as saden of the Husayn and Abbas shrines', in 1393. \n\nIn 1412, tensions grew between the Alid and non-Alid tribes as to the matters of the shrines'. For this reason Muhammad formed a number of groups, each representing a tribe, and designated a ''sarkoshk'' (leading minister) to lead each group.<ref name=\":57\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=45|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref> Muhammad died in 1423.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{Cite book|last=al-A'raji|first=Ja'far|url=https://archive.org/details/olomnasb_ymail_20160308_0846/page/n481/mode/2up|title=Manahil al-Dharab Fi Ansab al-Arab|publisher=Maktabat Ayatollah al-Mar'ashi al-Najafi|year=1998|isbn=|location=Qom, Iran|pages=481\u201382|language=Arabic|trans-title=Pool of Variety In The Lineages of the Arabs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Shaykh Salih|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=14iapnGgohsC&pg|title=al-Ain al-Basera Fi Matbu' Min al-Da'era|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-13-0|location=London, UK|pages=66|language=ar}}</ref>\n\n=== Tuma I Kamal al-Din al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Muhammad Sharaf al-Din. After the death of his father, in 1423, the governor of Baghdad, [[Shah Muhammad (Kara Koyunlu)|Shah Muhammad]], of the [[Kara Koyunlu|Black Sheep]] Turcomen tribe, made Tuma naqib of the ashraf, and saden of the Husayn and Abbas shrines'. Tuma died in 1442.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Madani|first=Dhamin bin Shadqam|url=https://archive.org/stream/olomnasb_ymail_1_20160904/%D8%AA%D8%AD%D9%81%D8%A9%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B2%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%20%D9%88%20%D8%B2%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%20%D9%81%D9%8A%20%D9%86%D8%B3%D8%A8%20%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%A7%D8%A1%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%A6%D9%85%D8%A9%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B7%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1%202#mode/2up|title=Tuhfat al-Azhar Wa Zulal al-Anhar Fi Nasab al-A'imah al-Athar|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=309|language=Arabic|trans-title=Vase of Flowers and Heavenly Rivers of The Lineages of The Imams}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Kamuna|first=Sayyid Abdul-Razaq|url=https://archive.org/details/mwardit7af/mode/2up|title=Mawared al-Athaf Fi Nuqaba' al-Ashraf|publisher=Matba'at al-Adab|year=1968|isbn=|volume=1|location=Najaf, Iraq|pages=151}}</ref>\n\n=== Sharaf al-Din al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Tuma I. Sharaf al-Din took the niqaba and sidana after his father, passed away in 1442, during the Black Sheep monarchy, and carried on during the [[Aq Qoyunlu|White Sheep]] monarchy. He passed down the niqaba and sidana to his son, Yahya, in 1493. He died in 1500.<ref name=\":0\" /> Iraqi historian, Dr. Imad Rauf in his book, ''al-Usar al-Hakima'', mentions he holds a document that has both Sharaf al-Din's name and [[Yaqub bin Uzun Hasan|Sultan Yaqub's]], dated from 1455.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Raouf|first=Imad Abdul-Salam|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=http://www.sooqukaz.com/index.php/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%B1/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%83%D9%85%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B6%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%82-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%87%D9%88%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D8%AA%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%AF-%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%B9%D8%A8%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%B1%D8%A4%D9%88%D9%81/download?p=1|title=al-Usar al-Hakima Wa Rijal al-Idara Wal Qadha Fi al-Iraq Fi Uhud al-Muta'akhira. 656\u20131337 AH.|publisher=Baghdad University|year=1992|isbn=|location=Baghdad, Iraq|pages=359|trans-title=Ruling Families and Men of Management and Law In Iraq In The Middle Ages. 1258\u20131918 AD.}}</ref>\n\n=== Yahya al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Sharaf al-Din. In 1493, Yahya took charge of the niqaba and sidana after his father. He died in 1536.<ref name=\":54\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=14|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Taj al-Din al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Tuma I. After the death of his nephew, Yahya in 1536, Taj al-Din took charge of the niqaba and sidana. He was naqib and saden until his death in 1556.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Alam al-Din al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Tuma II, the son of Sharaf al-Din. In 1573, the [[Sublime Porte]] issued a [[firman]], appointing Alam al-Din as the minister of [[Waqf|Charitable Endowments]] of Karbala. In November, 1589, he signed a power of attorney over all of his possessions to his son, Jameel; the document was witnessed by Muhammad-Ali al-Eshaiker and four other noblemen.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abd al-Sahib|url=https://jamalon.com/en/3081569.html|title=Buyutat Karbala al-Qadima|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2011|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=81-2|language=ar|trans-title=Old Households of Karbala}}</ref> He died in 1598.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul-Sahib|url=|title=Tarikh Karbala|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2018|isbn=|volume=3|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=70|language=Arabic|trans-title=HIstory of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Nasrallah al-Faizi ===\n{{main|Nasrallah al-Haeri}}\nHe was the son of Husayn, the son of Ali, the son of Yunis, the son of Jameel, the son of Alam al-Din. [[Nasrallah al-Haeri|Nasrallah]] was a senior [[Faq\u012bh|jurist]], [[teacher]], [[poet]], [[author]] and [[Annalists|annalist]]. He was the patriarch of the Nasrallah family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Musa Ibrahim|url=http://shiabooks.net/library.php?id=10195|title=al-Buyutat al-Adabiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Naqabat al-Mu'alimeen al-Markaziya|year=1968|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=491-497|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Literal Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Mehdi al-Faizi ===\nHe was the son of Hasan, the son of Mansur, the son of Nasir al-Din, the son of Yunis, the son of Jamil, the son of Alam al-Din. He was made saden of the Husayn shrine in 1752, until his death in 1790.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Muhammad-Hasan|title=Madinat al-Husayn|publisher=Matba'at Ahl al-Bayt|year=1969|isbn=|volume=1|location=Iraq|pages=77|trans-title=City of Husayn}}</ref> \n\n== Al Tuma ==\nAl Tuma ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0637\u0639\u0645\u0629|\u02be\u0100l \u1e6cu\u02bfma}}) branched off Tuma III al-Faizi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tehrani|first=Agha Bozorg|title=Tabaqat A'lam al-Shia|publisher=Dar Ihya al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2009|isbn=|volume=8|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=304-5|trans-title=Levels of the Shia's notables}}</ref> They own the famous [[Mukataa|muqata'a]] ''Fidan al-Sada'' which Tuma III endowed to his descendants in 1615, after it was granted to him by Sheikh Ahmed al-Nahawi. It is worthy to note that, t is a [[Waqf|khairi]] endowment, i.e. devoted to a charitable purpose from its inception, rather than for the benefit of his descendants. The family held custodianship of the Husayn shrine numerously throughout the last four centuries. It is currently one of the largest Alid families in Karbala. The family branched into five clans:<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=141\u201355|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n* Al Wahab\n* Al Mustafa (from this clan branched out Al Qotob, Al Fathallah and Al Urzuq)\n* Al Darwish (from this clan branched out Al Killidar, Al Sir-Khidma and Al Rowdha-Khan)\n* Al Muhammad (from this clan branched out Al Shurufi and Al Khemgeh)\n* Al Jawad\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n* '''Khalifah Nimatullah Tuma''' (d. 1697) was the grandson of Tuma III, he became the first of the descendants of Tuma III to hold the niqaba of Karbala, and this was in 1680. His grandson, Abbas also became naqib in 1773, but he died two months later.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kamuna|first=Abd al-Razzaq|url=https://archive.org/details/mwardit7af/mode/2up|title=Mawarid al-Athaf Fi al-Nuqaba al-Ashraf|publisher=Matba'at al-Adaab|year=1968|isbn=|volume=1|location=Najaf, Iraq|pages=151|language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Raouf|first=Imad Abd al-Salam|title=al-Usar al-Hakima|publisher=Dar al-Hikma|year=1991|isbn=|location=Baghdad, Iraq|pages=361|language=ar|trans-title=Ruling Families}}</ref>\n*'''Muhammad Jafar Tuma''' (d. 1835) was the saden of the Abbas shrine in 1834.<ref name=\":2\" />\n*'''Jawad 'al-Killidar' Hasan Tuma''' (d. 1891) was the saden of the Husayn shrine in 1874 until his death in 1891.<ref name=\":032\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=122-3|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref> His descendants took his nickname - ''al-Killidar'' (holder of the key) - as their family name, and are known as 'al-Killidar' or 'al-Killidar Tuma'.\n*'''Ali Jawad al-Killidar''' (d. 1900) was the saden of the Husayn shrine in 1891 until his death in 1900.<ref name=\":034\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=124|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref>\n*'''Muhammad-Hassan Kadhim Rowdha-Khan''' (1864\u20131945) was a religious scholar and [[orator]]. He was a leader in the [[Iraqi revolt of 1920|Iraqi revolt]] of 1920, and the first person to raise the [[Flag of the Arab Revolt|Arab (Iraqi) flag]] over Karbala's civic centre, causing him to be imprisoned by the [[British Army|British]]. He was freed at the behest of a senior cleric. He died whilst on pilgrimage to [[Imam Reza shrine|Imam Ridha]] in [[Mashhad]], in 1945, and his corpse was returned and buried in Karbala.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=147-48|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n*'''Abd al-Husayn Ali al-Killidar''' (1881\u20131960) was the saden of the Husayn shrine in 1900, until he passed it down to his son, Abd al-Salih in 1930.<ref name=\":035\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=125-6|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref> He authored a number of books on the history of Karbala, including ''Tarikh Karbala al-Mualla'' and ''Baghiyat al-Nubala Fi Tarikh Karbala''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Zirikli|first=Khayr al-Din|url=https://al-maktaba.org/book/12286/2750|title=al-A'lam|publisher=Dar al-'Ilm Lil Malayin|year=2002|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=278|language=ar|trans-title=The Notables}}</ref>\n*'''Dr. Abd al-Jawad Ali al-Killidar''' (1892\u20131959) was a doctor in Islamic history, and authored a number of books on the history of Karbala, including ''Tarikh Karbala'' and ''Ha'ir al-Husayn''. He founded the ''al-Ahrar'' newspaper in the 1930's.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Zirikli|first=Khayr al-Din|url=https://al-maktaba.org/book/12286/2750|title=al-A'lam|publisher=Dar al-'Ilm Lil Malayin|year=2002|isbn=|volume=3|location=|pages=276|language=ar|trans-title=The Notables}}</ref>\n*'''Abd al-Salih Abd al-Husayn al-Killidar''' (1911\u20132005) was a saden of the Husayn shrine in 1930 until he retired in 1981.<ref name=\":036\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=127|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref>[[File:Faisal_kilidar_1957.jpg|thumb|Abd al-Salih al-Killidar (centre left) during his sidanate with [[Faisal II of Iraq|King Faisal II]] (centre) in the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]], 1957.]]\n*'''Muhammad-Hassan Mustafa al-Killidar''' (1913\u20131995) was a celebrated author, most famous for his book ''Madinat al-Husayn'' (City of Hussain) which narrates a great deal of detail about the history of Karbala in numerous volumes. He was an advocate for women's rights, and issued a chain of articles titled 'The necessity of liberating women according to Islam'.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=al-Jibouri|first=Kaamil Salman|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bTE-CwAAQBAJ|title=Mu'jam al-'Udaba' Min 'Asr al-Jahili Hata Sanat 2002|publisher=Daar al-Kitab al-'Ilmiya|year=2003|isbn=|volume=5|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=237|language=Arabic|trans-title=Glossary of Scholars: From the Jahiliyyah to 2002 AD}}</ref>\n* '''Dr. Salih Jawad Tuma''' (b. 1929) is a doctor of Arabic and Comparative Literature. He is professor emeritus of East Asian Languages and Cultures at [[Indiana University]], and has been associated with the university since 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nelc.indiana.edu/people/emeriti-faculty/altoma-salih.html|title=Salih Altoma: Emeriti Faculty: People: Near Eastern Languages and Cultures: Indiana University Bloomington|website=Near Eastern Languages and Cultures|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.banipal.co.uk/contributors/364/salih-j-altoma/|title=Salih J Altoma|last=|first=|date=|website=www.banipal.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n* '''Salman Hadi Tuma''' (b. 1935) is a renowned author and poet. He is a graduate of [[University of Baghdad|Baghdad University's]] college of education, with many leading books on the history and culture of Karbala, as well as its notable figures.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=155|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n* '''Dr. Adnan Jawad Tuma''' (b. 1941) is a doctor in Language. He is a professor at [[University of Marburg|Philipps-Universit\u00e4t Marburg]]. He has authored a number of books and publications, focusing on Arabic calligraphy and religious manuscripts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n90674030/|title=Al-Toma, Adnan Jawad|last=|first=|date=|website=WorldCat Identities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Al-Toma|first=Adnan Jawad|url=https://archiv.ub.uni-marburg.de/eb/2017/0119/|title=Die arabischen Handschriften der Universit\u00e4tsbibliothek Marburg|date=2017|publisher=Philipps-Universit\u00e4t Marburg}}</ref>\n*'''Adil Abd al-Salih al-Killidar''' (b. 1942) was the saden of the Husayn shrine in 1981 until 1990. He was studying for his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Cairo]] in 1979, however he left it to attend to his duty as saden, which his father requested for him to take over.<ref name=\":037\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=128|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref>[[File:Mohaliadil.jpg|thumb|Adil al-Killidar (far right) during his sidanate with [[Muhammad Ali]] in the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]], 1990.]]\n*'''Ghiyath Jawad Tuma''' (b. 1956) is a scholar and orator. \n\n== Al Nasrallah ==\nAl Nasrallah ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0646\u0635\u0631\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647|\u02be\u0100l Na\u1e63r\u0100ll\u0101h}}) branched off [[Nasrallah al-Haeri|Nasrallah al-Faizi]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=al-Khalili|first=Ja'far|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=http://aljawadain.org/pdf/book-library/PDF/425.pdf|title=Mowsoo'at al-'Atabat al-Muqadassa (al-Kathimayn)|publisher=Mu'asasat al-A'lami lil-Matboo'at|year=1987|isbn=|volume=3|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=75|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Holy Shrines Encyclopedia (al-Kathimayn)}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|last=M\u016bsaw\u012b|first=\u02bbAbd al-Ras\u016bl|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aZfYAAAAMAAJ|title=al-Shia Fi al-Tarikh: 10-1421 AH / 1421-2000 AD|date=2001|publisher=Maktabat Madbuli al-Saghir|year=|isbn=977-208-323-X|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=193|language=ar}}</ref><ref name=\":53\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=24|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fgc8712.com/2016/12/21/%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d8%a7%d8%af%d8%a9-%d8%a2%d9%84-%d8%b7%d8%b9%d9%85%d8%a9-%d9%88%d8%a2%d9%84-%d9%86%d8%b5%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%84%d9%87/|title=al-Sada Aal Nasrallah|last=|first=|date=2016-12-21|website=Mashroo' Quraysh Wa Bani Hashim al-Geni|publisher=www.familytreedna.com|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Sayyid Family of House Nasrallah|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familytreedna.com/public/Iraq?iframe=yresults|title=FamilyTreeDNA - Iraq DNA Project|last=Nasrallah|first=Safaa|date=|website=www.familytreedna.com|others=Haplogroup: J-FGC30416|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> They own vast lands across Shfatha (now Ayn al-Tamur) and Karbala. Their grandfather Yunis al-Faizi excelled in business, and managed to purchase the muqata'a ''Maal Yunis'' which extended from the borders of Arba' Nahran to al-Jayya to Umm al-'Agareeg in Bab al-Salalma. He endowed his muqata'a to his descendants for their benefit. The family often held custodianship of the Husayn and Abbas' shrines. It is also the only Alid family to have two designated graveyards in the Husayn shrine, one near the old eighth ''kishwaniya'' (booth for depositing footwear), and the other near the tenth.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tuma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://archive.org/details/overalllibrary_gmail_20170224_1854/page/n147/mode/2up|title=Tarikh Marqad al-Husayn wal-Abbas|publisher=Mu'asasat al-A'lami|year=1996|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=147|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Husayn and Abbas Mausoleums}}</ref> It is also one of the largest Alid families in Karbala. The family branched into five clans:<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=229|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=24|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref>\n\n* Al Muhammad\n* Al Ahmed\n* Al Tawil\n* Al Salih\n* Al Muhammad-Ali\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n* '''Jawad Kathim Nasrallah''' (d. 1808) was the saden of the Husayn shrine after the [[Wahhabi sack of Karbala|sack]] of Karbala, in 1802 until his death in 1808.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=107|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref> With the help of the son of Sayyid Muhammad Mehdi al-Shahristani (d. 1801), he combined the mosque that headquartered the Sunni [[mufti]] of Karbala with the grand courtyard, forcing the garrison of Karbala, Amin Agha Turk<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.com/?id=obYxAAAAIAAJ&q=inauthor:%22Salm%C4%81n+H%C4%81d%C4%AB+%E1%B9%ACu%CA%BBmah%22&dq=inauthor:%22Salm%C4%81n+H%C4%81d%C4%AB+%E1%B9%ACu%CA%BBmah%22|title=Karbal\u0101\u02bc F\u012b al-Dh\u0101kirah|date=1988|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=43|language=ar|trans-title=Memories Of Karbala}}</ref>, to relocate the mufti to the small courtyard also known as the [[Buyid dynasty|Buyid]] graveyard.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul Sahib|title=Sidanat al-Rowdha al-Hussainiya wal-Abbasiya|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=128|language=Arabic|trans-title=Custodianship of The Shrines' of Hussain and Abbas}}</ref> In 1804, he supervised the expansion of the precinct of the grave, adding Ibrahim al-Mujab's grave and ''rawaq'' (hallway) to the north west side of the precinct<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatollah Dr. Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tKMHCgAAQBAJ&lpg|title=Tarikh al-Maraqid (al-Husayn, Wa Ahli Baytih, Wa Ansarih)|date=2002-12-01|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-902490-25-0|volume=2|location=London, UK|pages=122|language=ar|trans-title=}}</ref>.\n* '''Ali '<nowiki/>''al-Tawil''<nowiki/>'<nowiki/> Jawad Nasrallah''' was the saden of the Husayn shrine after his father Jawad, upon the royal decree issued by [[Sulayman Pasha the Little|Sulayman Pasha]], from 1808 until he was replaced on the orders of [[Fath-Ali Shah Qajar|Fath Ali Qajar]] in 1810, because he was allegedly too young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul Sahib|title=Sidanat al-Rowdha al-Hussainiya wal-Abbasiya|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=169\u201370|language=Arabic|trans-title=Custodianship of The Shrines' of Hussain and Abbas}}</ref> His descendants took his nickname - ''al-Tawil'' (the tall) - as their family name, and are known as 'al-Tawil''''<nowiki/><nowiki/><nowiki/>''' or 'al-Tawil Nasrallah'.\n* '''Ahmed Nasrallah Nasrallah''' was the saden of the Abbas shrine in 1867.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Nasrallah|first=Abdul Sahib|title=Sidanat al-Rowdha al-Hussainiya wal-Abbasiya|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=Arabic|trans-title=Custodianship of The Shrines' of Hussain and Abbas}}</ref>\n* '''Baqir Salih Nasrallah''' (d. 1886) was an Islamic missionary, that played a big role in the conversion of many of [[Tal Afar|Talafar]] to Shia Islam. He was known to have a remarkable level of physical strength, it is narrated on the account of Sayyid Ibrahim al-Isfahani in Sayyid Muhammad al-Hindi an-Najafi's ''kashkool'' (diary), that \"Sayyid Baqir was known for his exceptional strength, for he would stand on one leg on the edge of a well, and no man would be able to push him into the well.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Qazwini|first=Dr. Jawdat|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35671665--|title=al-Rawdh al-Khameel|publisher=al-Khazaen li-Ihya' al-Turath|year=|isbn=|volume=1|location=|pages=218|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Gardens of Love-Lies-Bleeding}}</ref>. This story resonates with the strength usually displayed by his ancestors' from the [[Hashim ibn Abd Manaf|Hashimite]] clan, and specifically [[Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyyah|Muhammad Ibn Al Hannafiyah]], who was known to be unmovable if he were to sit on the ground with his legs crossed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rizvi|first=Ghulam Murtuza|date=|title=Hazrat Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyyah|url=https://www.academia.edu/34055193|journal=|language=en|volume=|pages=4|quote=Sub Heading: Physical Stregnth of Mohammad Hanfiya|via=Academia}}</ref>\n* '''Hammoud Sultan Nasrallah''' (d. 1901) was head of the traders of Karbala in the Ottoman era, before the introduction of the chamber of commerce.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.com/?id=obYxAAAAIAAJ&q=inauthor:%22Salm%C4%81n+H%C4%81d%C4%AB+%E1%B9%ACu%CA%BBmah%22&dq=inauthor:%22Salm%C4%81n+H%C4%81d%C4%AB+%E1%B9%ACu%CA%BBmah%22|title=Karbal\u0101\u02bc F\u012b al-Dh\u0101kirah|date=1988|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=70|language=ar|trans-title=Memories Of Karbala}}</ref>\n* '''Dr. Murtadha Nasir Nasrallah''' (1922\u20131996) was a doctor of law, he worked as a professor at the [[University of Baghdad|University of Baghdad's]] business school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljawadain.org/flags-post.php?id=251|title=A'lam al-Kathimiyyah al-Muqadassa - al-'Ataba al-Kathimiya al-Muqadassa|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aljawadain.org|trans-title=Prominent Figures of Holy Kadhimiya - Holy Shrine of al-Kadhimayn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> He was a celebrated author, writing some of the leading books on corporation law.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Na\u1e63r All\u0101h|first=Murta\u1e0d\u00e1 N\u0101\u1e63ir|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/files/books/nyu_aco001416/nyu_aco001416_hi.pdf|title=al-Sharik\u0101t al-Tij\u0101r\u012byah|publisher=Ma\u1e6dba\u02bbat al-Irsh\u0101d|year=1969|isbn=|location=Baghdad, Iraq|pages=|language=Arabic|trans-title=Trading Companies|via=New York University Libraries}}</ref>\n* '''Hashim Hassan Nasrallah''' (1923\u20131997) was the chairman of the Karbala Chamber of Commerce for five terms from 1960 to 1969<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://k-coc.org/%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%af%d9%88%d8%b1%d8%a7%d8%aa-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a7%d9%86%d8%aa%d8%ae%d8%a7%d8%a8%d9%8a%d8%a9|title=Dowrat al-Intakhibya - Ghurfat Tijarat Karbala|last=|first=|date=|website=Karbala Chamber of Commerce|language=ar|trans-title=Election Terms of the Karbala Chamber of Commerce|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>. He supervised ''al-Iqtisad'' magazine that issued its first magazine in 15 July 1960.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.com/?id=obYxAAAAIAAJ&q=%D9%86%D8%B5%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87+%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1%D9%8A&dq=%D9%86%D8%B5%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87+%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1%D9%8A|title=Karbal\u0101\u02bc f\u012b al-dh\u0101kirah|date=1988|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=119|language=ar|trans-title=Memories Of Karbala}}</ref> He founded the Chamber's library in 1963.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://k-coc.org/alkrblaiien-early-traders-belonging-chamber-commerce-karbala-first-section/36|title=Awa'el al-Tujjar al-Karbala'iein al-Muntamin Ila Ghurfat Tijarat Karbala|last=|first=|date=|website=Karbala Chamber of Commerce|language=ar|trans-title=The early Karbalaei Businessmen to belong to the Karbala Chamber of Commerce|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>[[File:KCOC 1960s.jpg|thumb|Chairman Hashim Nasrallah (middle) and other members of the Karbala Chamber of Commerce, 1965.]]\n* '''Abd al-Sahib Nasir Nasrallah''' (b. 1953) was the saden of the Husayn shrine from 1991 to 2003.<ref name=\":033\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatullah Sheikh Sadiq|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AKMJBAAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Sidana al-Hussainiya|date=2014-02-01|publisher=Hussaini Charitable Trust|year=|isbn=978-1-908286-99-4|location=|pages=130|language=Arabic|trans-title=The History of the Custodianship of Imam Hussain's Shrine}}</ref> He is also an author with many published books, mostly about the history of Karbala.\n* '''Dr. Hashim Muhammad al-Tawil''' (b. 1955) is a doctor of art history, he is the Tenured Professor and Chair of Art History Area Studies at [[Henry Ford College]], [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]], [[Michigan|MI]]. He has also been an advisory board member at the Arab Cultural Studies Program in Henry Ford College since 2011, and a Board of Directors member in the Asian & Islamic Art Forum of the Detroit Institute of Arts since 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hfcc.edu/academics/programs/art-foundations/faculty/hashim-al-tawil-phd|title=Hashim Al-Tawil, Ph.D.|website=Henry Ford College|language=en|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n* '''Muhammad-Hussain Muhammad-Ali Nasrallah''' (b. 1951) is a retired [[judge]]. He held custodianship of the Husayn shrine after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|US invasion]], until a secretary general was appointed by [[Ali al-Sistani|Ayatollah Sistani]] in 2003 as part of the constitutional transition of the shrines' management to the Shi'i Endowment Office<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Ayatollah Dr. Mohammed Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8PBMO3bSN1AC&lpg|title=Tarikh al-Maraqid (al-Husayn Wa Ahli Baytih Wa Ansarih)|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-902490-37-3|volume=4|location=London, UK|pages=377|language=ar|trans-title=Shrine History (Hussain, his family and companions)}}</ref>. He was appointed as Vice President of the Appeals Tribunal court in [[Babil Governorate|Babil]] in 2003, after which he became the President of the Appeals Tribunal court in [[Wasit, Iraq|Wasit]], in 2004. In 2005, he established the Appeals Tribunal court in Karbala and became its president. In 2007, he became the President of the Appeals Tribunal court of [[Muthanna Governorate|al-Muthanna]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://burathanews.com/arabic/news/9412|title=Sada Jum'at Karbala al-Muqadassa Fi Mu'asasat al-Qadhaa' al-'Ulya|last=|first=|date=2006-10-14|website=Buratha News Outlet|language=ar-iq|trans-title=Karbala's Friday Echoes For The Supreme Judicial Institutions|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> He was also a member of the Judicial Supervisory Authority of the [[Supreme Judicial Council of Iraq|Supreme Judicial Council]] supervising the courts of Babil, Wasit, Najaf and [[Al Diwaniyah|al-Diwaniya]] until his retirement in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.non14.net/public/5400|title=al-Sudani Sayuhal Ila al-Qadha Qareeban Wa Shukook Hawl Wujudah Fil Bilad|last=|first=|date=|website=Noon News Outlet|language=Arabic|trans-title=al-Sudani Will Fall Into the Hands of the Law And Doubts of His Presence In The Country|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> He was nominated [[Ministry of Justice (Iraq)|Minister of Justice]] in 2016 as part of [[Muqtada al-Sadr|Muqtada al-Sadr's]] attempt at establishing a technocratic government in Iraq<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iraqkhair.com/%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%8a%d8%af-%d9%85%d8%ad%d9%85%d8%af-%d9%86%d8%b5%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%84%d9%87-%d9%85%d8%b1%d8%b4%d8%ad%d8%a7-%d9%84%d9%88%d8%b2%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b9%d8%af%d9%84/|title=Sayyid Mohammed Nasrallah Murashahan li-Wizarat al-'Adl|last=|first=|date=|website=Shabakat Iraq al-Khayr|language=ar|trans-title=Sayyid Mohammed Nasrallah Nominated For Ministry of Justice|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-08|quote=He is the son of Karbala, from the noble al-Fa'iz al-Musawi family. He is President of the Appeals Tribunal of Karbala, and previously al-Muthanna.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2016/2/13/powerful-iraqi-cleric-muqtada-sadr-calls-for-technocratic-government|title=Powerful cleric al-Sadr calls for 'technocratic government' in Iraq|last=|first=|date=|website=TheNewArab|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ar/\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629/\u0623\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621-\u062a\u0634\u0643\u064a\u0644\u0629-\u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0637-\u0627\u0644\u062a\u064a-\u0642\u062f\u0645\u0647\u0627-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u0627\u062f\u064a-\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0631\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u064a/547433|title=Asma' Tashkilat Hukumat al-Teknoqrat Alaty Qadamaha al-Ebadi lil-Barlaman al-Iraqi|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aa.com.tr|language=Arabic|trans-title=List of names nominated for the Technocratic Government PM al-Abadi presented to the Iraqi parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>. He is a Law Representative for Pillsbury Global in Iraq. He is currently the chief of the Nasrallah family, a post he has held since 2017.[[File:Technocrat Lineup.jpg|thumb|Muhammad-Husayn Nasrallah (centre) during the technocratic government's press conference with [[Muqtada al-Sadr]] (far left) in [[Najaf]], 2016.]]\n*'''Dr. Hasan Ali Nasrallah''' (b. 1951) is a doctor of internal medicine, and the dean of the Medical College of the [[University of Karbala]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://medicine.uokerbala.edu.iq/wp/blog/2016/02/23/dr-hasan-naseroallah/|title=Hasan Ali Abbod Nasrallah|last=|first=|date=|website=College of Medicine - University of Karbala|language=ar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uokerbala.edu.iq/archives/3977|title=Kuliyat al-Tibb Fi Jamiat Karbala Tabhath Ma'a Wafd Min Jami'at Sheffield|last=Kassim|first=Maher|date=|website=University of Kerbala|language=ar|trans-title=College of Medicine of University of Karbala coordinates with University of Sheffield|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n*'''Arif Muhammad Nasrallah''' (b. 1958) is a social activist<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Khazraji|first=Dr Nadhir|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ee2KDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA614&dq=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF+%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%81+%D9%86%D8%B5%D8%B1+%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87#v=onepage&q=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF%20%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%81%20%D9%86%D8%B5%D8%B1%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87&f=false|title=Safar al-Khulud: Rihlat al-Mowsoo'a al-Husayniya Min Mamlakat al-Dhabab Ila Jumhuriyat al-Qibab|date=2019-01-01|publisher=Beyt al-'Ilm Lil Nabiheen|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=The Journey Of Salvation: The HCR's Journey From The Kingdom Of Fog To The Republic Of Domes}}</ref>, he is the chairman of the al-Wala' wal-Fida' wal-Fath Association, and in 2008, was the first person to take a religious convoy to [[Samarra]] after the [[2006 al-Askari mosque bombing|2006]] and [[2007 al-Askari mosque bombing|2007]] bombings, later calling for the [[Marja'|maraja]]' of Iraq and the Iraqi government to take action in securing and rebuilding the [[Al-Askari Shrine|al-Askariyayn]] shrines<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nahrainnet.net/news/52/ARTICLE/11174/2008-03-17.html/|title=Li Awal Mara Munth Tafjeer Marqaday al-Askariyayn - Masirat Aza' Min Karbala Ila Samarra|last=|first=|date=|website=Nahrain Net News Website|language=ar|trans-title=First Time Since The Bombing Of Al-Askariyayn Mosque - A Procession From Karbala to Samarra|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-03|layurl=https://www.yahosein.com/vb/node/98366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yazahra.org/1/Samaraa/benaa%20samaraa/1.htm|title=Rihlat al-Walaa' Ila Samarra Kan Laha 'Athar Baligh Fi Nasb Dharih Fi al-Rowdha al-Askariya|last=|first=|date=|website=www.yazahra.org|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Impact of al-Wala Association's visit to Samarra on rebuilding the grave of Imam al-Askari and Imam al-Hadi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. He is also the director of [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Ayatollah Shirazi's]] public relations office in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english.shirazi.ir/6926/|title=PR Manager Aref Nasrullah of Grand Ayatollah Shirazi Visits Military, Political and Social Figures|last=|first=|date=2019-04-29|website=Office of the Grand Shia Jurist Ayatollah Sayid Sadiq Al-Shirazi|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rudaw.net/arabic/middleeast/iraq/171220192|title=Multaqa Erbil-Najaf Rai' Jidan Wa Na'mal An Yakun al-Multaqa al-Qadim Fi al-Najaf|last=|first=|date=|website=R\u00fbdaw Research Centre|language=ar|trans-title=Arif Nasrallah: The Erbil-Najaf conference is amazing, and we hope the next conference is in Najaf|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Al Dhiya al-Din ==\nAl Dhiya al-Din ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0636\u064a\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646|\u02be\u0100l \u1e0chiya\u02be \u0101l-Din}}) branched off Dhiya al-Din al-Faizi. They own lands in ''Umm Ramila'' in Shfatha, and in Karbala, they own the famous farm, ''Dhway,'' which they were on some occasions named after. Dhway was endowed by Yahya, to his son, Dhiya al-Din and his descendants, in 1799, for the benefit of the Husayn Shrine.<ref name=\":56\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=26|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref> The family held the custodianship of the Abbas shrine numerous times throughout the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=134\u201337|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n*'''Husayn Muhammad-Ali Dhiya al-Din''' (d. 1871) was the saden of the Abbas shrine in 1864 until his death in 1871.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=136|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n*'''Mustafa Husayn Dhiya al-Din''' (d. 1879) was the saden of the Abbas shrine after his fathers death, until his death in 1879.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*'''Murtadha Mustafa Dhiya al-Din''' (1869\u20131938) was the saden of the Abbas shrine after his fathers death, until his death in 1938. When his father died, he was still too young to take on the duty of the sidana, so it was held by Muhammad-Mehdi Tuma, until he was reported to the governor of Baghdad, Abd al-Rahman Pasha.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hukam.net/family.php?twn=85#5613|title=BAGHDAD|last=|first=|date=|website=Hukam|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Abd al-Rahman reinstated Murtadha, upon receiving the news. He also issued a firman to solidify Murtadha's position, however his uncle Abbas Dhiya al-Din took responsibility, until Murtadha came of age, as he was only ten years old.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Killidar|first=Muhammad-Hassan|title=Madinat al-Husayn|publisher=|year=|isbn=|volume=1|location=|pages=89-90|language=ar|trans-title=City of Husayn}}</ref>[[File:King Faisal I Abbas shrine.jpg|thumb|Murtadha Dhiya al-Din (centre right) during his sidanate with [[Faisal I of Iraq|King Faisal I]] (centre) in the [[Imam Husayn Shrine|Abbas shrine]], 1921.]]\n*'''Muhammad-Hassan Murtadha Dhiya al-Din''' (d. 1953) was the saden of the Abbas shrine after his fathers death in 1938. He was one of the main contributors to the peace treaty between the people of [[Kadhimiya]] and the people of Najaf on [[Ashura]] of 1946. He also prevented the police from entering the Abbas shrine during the [[Iraqi Intifada (1952)|1952 revolt]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=136-37|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n*'''Badr al-Din 'Badri' Muhammad-Hassan''' (d. 1985) was the saden of the Abbas shrine after his fathers death in 1953. He retired from his responsibilities in 1982.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=137|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>[[File:Hakimabbas.jpg|thumb|Badri Dhiya al-Din (centre right) during his sidanate with [[Muhsin al-Hakim|Ayatollah Muhsin al-Hakim]] (centre) in the Abbas shrine, 1966.]]\n*'''Muhammad-Husayn Mehdi Dhiya al-Din''' was the saden of the Abbas shrine in 1982 until 1991.<ref name=\":4\" />\n*'''Ahmed Abbod Dhiya al-Din''' (d. 2015) was a renowned merchant. He opened a number of businesses in ''mulk'' (parade) Al Nasrallah. He is the first person to bring the [[Radio receiver|radio]] and [[television]] to Karbala.\u00a0 He was known as ''balur'' (crystal) because he owned a large crystal store. He was the chief of the Dhiya al-Din family until his death.\n\n== Al Tajir ==\nAl Tajir ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u062a\u0627\u062c\u0631|\u02be\u0100l T\u0101\u01e7ir}}) branched off Ali 'al-Tajir' al-Faizi. Ali was named ''al-Tajir'' (the merchant), due to his frequent travels to East Asia for trade. The family own farms known as ''Umm al-Sudan'' in [[mahala]]t Al Faiz (now known as al-Hayabi), that Hassan al-Tajir endowed to his descendants in 1680. The family served in the holy Husayn and Abbas shrines'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=34\u201335|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n* '''Muhammad Ali Tajir''' was the sarkoshk of the Ha'iri group of custodians of the two shrines in the late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tKMHCgAAQBAJ|title=Tarikh al-Maraqid (al-Husayn, Wa Ahli Baytih Wa Ansarih)|date=2002-12-01|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-902490-25-0|volume=2|location=London, UK|pages=48|language=ar|trans-title=History of the Shrines (Husayn, his family and his companions)}}</ref> \n\n== Al Ouj ==\nAl Ouj ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0639\u0648\u062c|\u02be\u0100l \u02bfOu\u01e7}}) branched off Muhsin Ouj al-Faizi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tamimi|first=Mohammed Ali|url=http://shiabooks.net/library.php?id=9307|title=Mashhad al-Imam Aw Madinat an-Najaf|publisher=al-Maktaba al-Haydaria|year=2010|isbn=|volume=4|location=Qom, Iran|pages=256|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Shrine of the Imam or The City of Najaf}}</ref> They have a partful ownership in Tuma III's Fidan al-Sada muqata'a. They also own parts of the farms known as ''Maal al-Saghir'', in mahalat Al Faiz, endowed in 1847 and ''Maal Ju'an'', near mahalat Al Faiz, endowed in 1853. The family served in the holy Husayn and Abbas shrines'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=164-5|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n* '''Abd al-Amir Jawad Ouj''' (1958\u20132011) was a author and poet. He obtained a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in Project Planning and Management and pursued a career in writing and journalism. He has authored numerous books, including leading books on genealogy and Islamic folklore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.non14.net/public/31180|title=al-Mu'arikh Abdul Amir 'Ouj Yatahadath 'An (Soorat Karbala al-Mansiya) Fi Kitab Qayd al-Tab'|last=al-Banay|first=Salam|date=|website=Non News Outlet|language=ar|trans-title=Historian Abd al-Amir Ouj speaks about 'Images from Forgotten Karbala' in his yet to be published book|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> He disappeared in 2011, and has been missing since.\n\n== Al Sayyid Amin ==\nAl Sayyid Amin ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u0644 \u0633\u064a\u062f \u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646|\u02be\u0100l Sayyid \u0100min}}) branched off Muhammad-Amin al-Faizi, also known as Sayyid Amin al-Faizi. They also own lands in Ayn al-Tamur that Muhammad-Amin endowed to his descendants in 1703. The family have an official Ottoman firman confirming this.<ref name=\":55\">{{Cite book|last=Shams al-Din|first=Sayyid Ibrahim|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%83%D8%AA%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE/page/689|title=al-Buyutat al-'Alawiya Fi Karbala|publisher=Matba'at Karbala|year=|isbn=|location=Karbala, Iraq|pages=28|language=Arabic|trans-title=The Alid Households In Karbala}}</ref> The family served in the holy Husayn and Abbas shrines'.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tu'ma|first=Salman Hadi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=belqrgEACAAJ|title='Asha'ir Karbala Wa Usarha|publisher=Dar al-Muhja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=24\u201325|language=Arabic|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref> Today they are known as Al Jolokhan al-Faizi, as they married into, Al Jolokhan from Al Zheek, and took on their name in the late 19th century.<ref name=\":55\" />\n\n=== Notable members ===\n\n*'''Muhammad-Ali Muhammad Jolokhan''' (1928\u20132007) was a renowned cleric and orator. His descendants took his mother's surname - ''Jolokhan'' - as their family name, and are known as 'Jolokhan' or 'Jolokhan al-Faizi'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.holykarbala.net/v2/index.php/ar/%D9%85%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%86%D8%A9-%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%82%D8%AF%D8%B3%D8%A9-3/%D8%A3%D8%B9%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1/%D8%AE%D8%AF%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%85%D9%86%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B3%D9%8A%D9%86%D9%8A/422-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF-%D8%AC%D9%84%D9%88%D8%AE%D8%A7%D9%86|title=Sayyid Muhammad Jolokhan|last=|first=|date=|website=Holy Karbala Network|language=ar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Family Tree ==\nSources:<ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Shubbar|first=Jawad|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=http://aljawadain.org/pdf/book-library/PDF/393.pdf|title='Adab al-Taff Wa Shu'ara' al-Husayn|publisher=Dar al-Murtadha|year=1988|isbn=|volume=5|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=251|language=Arabic|trans-title=Literature of Taff and the Poets of Husayn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mohammed|first=al-Tanji 'Ibn Battuta'|url=https://download-library-pdf-ebooks.com/18013-free-book|title=Tu\u1e25fet \u00fcl-Nuth\u0101r F\u012b Ghar\u0101'ib il-Em\u1e63\u0101r Wa 'Ajai'b al-Asf\u0101r|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-'Ulum|year=1987|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=231|language=Arabic|trans-title=A Masterpiece to Those Who Contemplate the Wonders of Cities and the Marvels of Travelling}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fgc8712.com/category/by49997/|title=BY49997 - Natijat al-Sada al-Fa'iz [Al Faiz Result]|last=|first=|date=|website=Mashroo' Quraysh Wa Bani Hashim al-Geni|language=ar|trans-title=Quraysh and Bani Hashim Genic Project|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n{{chart/start|style=font-size:90%; line-height: 120%; margin:1em;|align=center}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |001|001='''[[Hashim ibn Abd Manaf|Hashim]]'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |002|002={{nowrap|'''[[Abdul-Muttalib]]'''}}}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|^|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |004| | | | | |003|003='''[[Abdullah ibn Abdul-Muttalib|Abdullah]]'''|004={{nowrap|'''[[Abu Talib ibn Abd al-